, "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to heated discharge plume", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2", "aqueous": false, "other": "electric discharge / volcanic lightning; radical recombination of CH3\u2022 and HS\u2022"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge generates methyl and hydrosulfide radicals that recombine to form methanethiol directly in the gas phase.", "reasoning": "The report explicitly states that spark discharge and volcanic lightning can directly generate methanethiol from CH4 and H2S through radical recombination, and that this is the route operative in Miller-type methionine-producing experiments (Van Trump & Miller, 1972; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Acrolein formation by aldol-condensation corridor from formaldehyde and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "very dilute aldehydes; neutral to basic aqueous conditions; evaporitic concentration can assist"}, "mechanism": "Aldol addition followed by dehydration converts formaldehyde/acetaldehyde-derived carbonyl chemistry into the \u03b1,\u03b2-unsaturated aldehyde acrolein.", "reasoning": "This reaction follows the specific validated acrolein route emphasized in the report and corrects prior oversimplification. Cleaves demonstrated acrolein formation from very dilute aldehyde solutions under neutral to basic aqueous conditions, establishing prebiotic plausibility. The report identifies acrolein as the pivotal branching intermediate for methionine chemistry (Cleaves, 2003; Van Trump & Miller, 1972)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Michael addition of methanethiol to acrolein forming methional", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "mild aqueous conditions; thiolate conjugate addition"}, "mechanism": "Methanethiol, via its thiolate form, undergoes 1,4-conjugate addition to acrolein to yield 3-methylthiopropionaldehyde (methional), creating the thioether bond of methionine.", "reasoning": "The report states that all experimentally verified prebiotic methionine syntheses converge on this Michael addition step, which forms the characteristic thioether bond and yields methional as the direct Strecker precursor (Van Trump & Miller, 1972; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Strecker synthesis of methionine aminonitrile from methional", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "aqueous Strecker conditions in anoxic setting"}, "mechanism": "Methional forms an imine/iminium with ammonia that is trapped by cyanide to produce the corresponding \u03b1-aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the key Strecker step in the only proven methionine route. The report specifically identifies reaction of methional with HCN and ammonia to form an \u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate prior to hydrolysis. Industrial racemic methionine synthesis follows the same logic, and Van Trump & Miller established it as prebiotically robust (Van Trump & Miller, 1972; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis of methionine aminonitrile to methionine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable, mild to moderately heated aqueous cycling", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "prolonged hydrolysis during pool cycling or