ied methionine corridor. Main remaining issue is geochemical integration of the precursor pools.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_003\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Explicitly define supercritical CO2 and MoS2 conditions in the pathway metadata.\",\n        \"Add a basin-interface scenario linking hydrothermal sulfur chemistry to surface organic chemistry.\",\n        \"Indicate how methanethiol is retained against volatilization.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.79,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.93,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.97,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.96,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.91,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.97,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.97,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.94,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is effectively the classic Miller sulfur-rich discharge route and is among the most experimentally defensible in the network. It directly reflects the 1958 archived experiment reanalyzed in 2011 and the 1972 acrolein/methional proposal. As with P1, the main issue is that some early discharge precursor reactions are idealized as direct conversions rather than atmospheric product networks.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_003\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Model discharge chemistry as arising from a gas mixture rather than individual pairwise reactants.\",\n        \"Add explicit mention of H2S-rich volcanic lightning conditions.\",\n        \"Include product-mixture language for aldehyde formation.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.62,\n      