ears somewhat unnecessary and weakens coherence.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_011"], "suggestions": ["Either make the route fully surface-based or provide a strong transport rationale for hydrothermal aldehydes.", "Specify why hydrothermal aldehydes are preferred over directly discharge-generated aldehydes.", "Document expected concentration mechanisms for acrolein-forming aldehydes after hydrothermal export."]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.86, "rxn_003": 0.79, "rxn_004": 0.88, "rxn_007": 0.93, "rxn_008": 0.97, "rxn_001": 0.94, "rxn_009": 0.96, "rxn_010": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.89, "pathway_coherence": 0.95, "environmental_progression": 0.93, "target_achievement": 0.97, "overall_confidence": 0.92, "feedback": "This is essentially the inverse of P2 and remains a strong route. Surface aldehyde and HCN generation are literature-supported, and hydrothermal FeS methanethiol production addresses the sulfur bottleneck. The route is realistic if methanethiol can be transported or trapped into surface evaporitic systems at sufficient concentrations.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004"], "suggestions": ["Add concentration mechanisms such as evaporitic pooling or adsorption to mineral surfaces.", "Clarify that hydrothermal methanethiol production is moderate-temperature and not black-smoker style.", "Tighten the stoichiometric description of acetaldehyde formation."]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_002": 0.86, "rxn_003": 0.79, "rxn_005": 0.92, "rxn_007": 0.93, "rxn_008": 0.97, "rxn_001": 0.94, "rxn_009": 0.96, "rxn_010": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.91, "pathway_coherence": 0.95, "environmental_progression": 0.93, "target_achievement": 0.97, "overall_confidence": 0.93, "feedback": "This is one of the best mixed-environment pathways. Surface generation of HCN and aldehydes is well supported, and MoS2-mediated methanethiol synthesis is the strongest non-discharge solution t